#a. The company offers a money-back guarantee that at most 1 disk in a pack will be defective. Any pack that exceeds this amount can be returned for a full refund. What is the chance that you buy only one pack and qualify for a refund?
pbinom(1,10,.01, lower.tail=F) # Any more than 1 disk out of 10 and you are elligible for a refund
## [1] 0.004266
#Suppose you bought 10 packs of disks. Each pack is independent of the others. What is the chance that you could claim a refund on more than one pack
pbinom(1, 10, pbinom(1,10,.01,lower.tail=F), lower.tail=F)
## [1] 0.0008006
#A quality-control inspector is randomly sampling and testing disks as they come off the assembly line. What is the probability that he has to sample no more than 10 disks to get his first defective one?
pnbinom(10,1, .01)
## [1] 0.1047
#The package of disks you just bought contains two defective disks, but you won't find that out until you use them. Bummer! You need to use three disks to make backups of your precious statistics exam. What is the chance that none of the disks you pick are defective?
dhyper(3,8,2,3)
## [1] 0.4667

  1. What would be the pdf f(x) for X, given F(x)?

Simply finding \(f(x)\ =\ F(x)\prime{},\ f(x)\ =\ \frac{2x}{a^2}\)

  1. In general, the function F(x) exists and is continuous over the entire real number line. Why is it necessary to restrict its domain to values between 0 and a (inclusive) for the random variable X?

\(at\ x\ =\ 0,\ \frac{x^2}{a^2}\ =\ 0,\ and\ as\ x\ \rightarrow{}\ a,\ \frac{x^2}{a^2}\ \rightarrow{}\ 1\) This is important in the CDF because probability distributions can only lie somewhere between 0, and 1 as they are a sum of all of the probabilities in that distribution

  1. In order to calculate the different parts of the 5 number summary,we need to solve for key points of data.

# Create a contingency table by gender, in order to find which percentage of the population of the gender had specific goals
round(prop.table(table(popData$Goals, popData$Gender), 2) * 100,digits=1)
##          
##            boy girl
##   Grades  51.5 51.8
##   Popular 22.0 36.3
##   Sports  26.4 12.0

# Read the dataset from Dr Thomleys website
antData<-read.csv(file=url("http://www1.appstate.edu/~thomleyje/data-files/Anthropometric.csv"))

males<-subset(antData, Gender=='Male')
females<-subset(antData, Gender=='Female')



hist(antData$Height, prob=T, main="Histogram", xlab="Height (inches)", ylab="frequency")
curve(dnorm(x,mean(antData$Height), sd(antData$Height)), col="RED", add=T)

qqnorm(antData$Height, main="QQ Plot for Aggregate Data")
qqline(antData$Height, col="red")

plot.ecdf(antData$Height, main="ECDF Plot for Aggregate Data")
curve(pnorm(x,mean(antData$Height),sd(antData$Height)),col="red",add=T)

hist(males$Height, prob=T, main="Male Height Histogram", xlab="Height (inches)", ylab="frequency")
curve(dnorm(x,mean(males$Height), sd(males$Height)), col="RED", add=T)

qqnorm(males$Height, main="QQ for Males")
qqline(males$Height, col="red")

plot.ecdf(males$Height, main="ECDF for Males")
curve(pnorm(x,mean(males$Height),sd(males$Height)),col="red",add=T)

hist(females$Height, prob=T, main="Female height Histogram", xlab="Height (inches)", ylab="frequency")
curve(dnorm(x,mean(females$Height), sd(females$Height)), col="RED", add=T)

# Create the QQNorm Plot
qqnorm(females$Height, main="Female QQ Plot")
qqline(females$Height, col="red")

# Create the ECDF plot
plot.ecdf(females$Height, main="Female ECDF Plot")
curve(pnorm(x,mean(females$Height),sd(females$Height)),col="red",add=T)

# Make box plots
boxplot(antData$Height, males$Height, females$Height, names=c("Total Set", "Males", "Females"), ylab="Height (inches)", main="Height Distribution", horizontal=T)

# They all appear relatively normal, the females curve looks more normal than the males, which appear to have a slight left skew.
